<P><STRONG>TextureTorus</STRONG> is a C++ program illustrating the use =
of=20
OpenGL. &nbsp; It is intended to accompany the book <EM><STRONG>3D =
Computer=20
Graphics: A mathematical approach with OpenGL</STRONG>, </EM>by S. Buss, =

Cambridge University Press, 2003. &nbsp; However, it can be used =
independently=20
as well.</P>
<P><STRONG>TextureTorus </STRONG>draws a torus in a non-standard way, as =
a=20
ribbon of quad strips that wrap around the torus in one long =
strip.&nbsp; The C=20
code consists of two source files, <STRONG>TextureTorus.cpp</STRONG> and =

<STRONG>TextureTorus.h.</STRONG>&nbsp;&nbsp; There are several options =
available=20
for downloading this program:=20
<UL>
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.math.ucsd.edu/~sbuss/MathCG/OpenGLsoft/TextureTorus/Te=
xtureTorusProject.zip">TextureTorusProject.zip</A>:=20
  A zip file, including the source files, Microsoft Visual C++ workspace =
and=20
  project files, and Win32 executable.=20
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.math.ucsd.edu/~sbuss/MathCG/OpenGLsoft/TextureTorus/Te=
xtureTorus.zip">TextureTorus.zip</A>:=20
  A zip file, with sources files and the executable.=20
  <LI><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.math.ucsd.edu/~sbuss/MathCG/OpenGLsoft/TextureTorus/Te=
xtureTorus.cpp">TextureTorus.cpp</A>=20
  and <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.math.ucsd.edu/~sbuss/MathCG/OpenGLsoft/TextureTorus/Te=
xtureTorus.h">TextureTorus.h</A>=20
  and <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.math.ucsd.edu/~sbuss/MathCG/OpenGLsoft/TextureTorus/Te=
xtureTorus.exe">TextureTorus.exe</A>=20
  and <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.math.ucsd.edu/~sbuss/MathCG/OpenGLsoft/TextureTorus/Wo=
odGrain.bmp">WoodGrain.bmp</A>:&nbsp;=20
  Download the two source files, the executable, and the bitmapped =
texture, one=20
  at a time. </LI></UL>
<P><STRONG>Things to try out:</STRONG>=20
<OL>
  <LI>Before running <STRONG>TextureTorus,</STRONG> you should try out =
the=20
  simpler <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.math.ucsd.edu/~sbuss/MathCG/OpenGLsoft/WrapTorus/WrapT=
orus.html"><STRONG>WrapTorus</STRONG></A>=20
  and <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.math.ucsd.edu/~sbuss/MathCG/OpenGLsoft/LightTorus/Ligh=
tTorus.html"><STRONG>LightTorus</STRONG></A>=20
  programs.&nbsp; For a simpler setting illustrating the use of =
textures, see=20
  <STRONG><A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.math.ucsd.edu/~sbuss/MathCG/OpenGLsoft/TextureBMP/Text=
ureBMP.html">TextureBMP</A>.</STRONG>=20

  <LI>Compile and run the program.&nbsp; Test out the keyboard =
controls.&nbsp;=20
  The very last control (only) is new and not in =
<STRONG>LightTorus.</STRONG>
  <OL type=3Da>
    <LI>Press arrow keys (left, right, up and down) to make the torus =
rotate.=20
    <LI>Press "s" to single step the animation,=20
    <LI>Press "a" to start the animation running again without =
stopping.&nbsp;=20
    (Undoes the "s" effect.)=20
    <LI>Press "r" to reset the torus back to its original orientation =
with no=20
    velocity.=20
    <LI>Press "0" (zero) to zero the velocity of the torus, but leave =
its=20
    position fixed.=20
    <LI>Press "W" to increase the number of wraps,&nbsp; "w" to decrease =
the=20
    number of wraps.=20
    <LI>Press "N" to increase the number of segments per wrap.&nbsp; "n" =
to=20
    decrease the number of segments per wrap.=20
    <LI>Press "q" to toggle between drawing quadrangles and triangles.=20
    <LI>Press "p" to toggle between rendering in filled polygon mode, =
and in=20
    wireframe mode.=20
    <LI>Press "f" to toggle between flat shading and smooth shading.=20
    <LI>Press "0" (zero) and "1" (one) to toggle the lights (Light #0 =
and light=20
    #1) off and on.=20
    <LI>Press "l" to toggle local mode off and on.&nbsp; This command =
switches=20
    between having a local viewer and a positional light and having a =
non-local=20
    viewer (i.e., positioned at a point at infinity) and a directional =
light.=20
    <LI>Press "t" to toggle the texture off and on. </LI></OL>
  <LI>Observe the diffuse lighting, and how the lightness of the =
textured torus=20
  chnges with the brightness of the diffuse lighting.&nbsp; Note that =
specular=20
  highlights are not visible.. </LI></OL>
